1
00:00:58,520 --> 00:01:00,556
<i>What a spectacle.</i>

2
00:01:02,200 --> 00:01:05,158
<i>Millions and millions of stars.</i>

3
00:01:07,440 --> 00:01:10,113
<i>Funny thing, the universe.</i>

4
00:01:11,360 --> 00:01:14,158
<i>Sort of scares the shit out of you,</i>
<i>doesn't it?</i>

5
00:01:14,640 --> 00:01:17,234
<i>So where did it</i>
<i>all come from, do you think?</i>

6
00:01:17,320 --> 00:01:19,311
<i>Don't know.</i>

7
00:01:19,760 --> 00:01:21,876
<i>Just happened, I suppose.</i>

8
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:25,991
<i>So, what about when we die?</i>

9
00:01:26,680 --> 00:01:28,477
<i>Nothing.</i>

10
00:01:28,560 --> 00:01:30,278
<i>Nothing at all?</i>

11
00:01:44,560 --> 00:01:47,597
What fathead has caused all this?

12
00:01:49,200 --> 00:01:52,476
Listen... the first race has started.

13
00:01:54,880 --> 00:01:56,313
Ridiculous.

14
00:01:56,800 --> 00:01:58,392
All that money to sit in a queue.

15
00:01:58,480 --> 00:02:01,677
Arthur! Just relax, will you?

16
00:02:04,600 --> 00:02:06,079
I know, how about a song?

17
00:02:16,200 --> 00:02:18,509
- There's been an accident.
- Where?!

18
00:02:18,600 --> 00:02:21,068
I don't know, do I, fathead?!

19
00:02:21,160 --> 00:02:23,594
That's what we're gonna find out.

20
00:02:27,440 --> 00:02:30,637
Why can't you just sit and wait
like everybody else?

21
00:02:30,720 --> 00:02:33,518
- Show them the stethoscope, pet.
- What for?

22
00:02:33,600 --> 00:02:36,398
- Let them know we're doctors.
- We'll do no such thing.

23
00:02:36,480 --> 00:02:40,359
- What are you doing?
- It's all right. I'm a doctor.

24
00:02:40,440 --> 00:02:43,352
I'm a doctor, there's been an accident.
I'm a doctor.

25
00:02:45,560 --> 00:02:48,279
<i>This is the way</i>
<i>that it was with my father.</i>

26
00:02:48,360 --> 00:02:51,033
<i>Minor duplicities.</i>
<i>Little fiddles.</i>

27
00:02:51,120 --> 00:02:54,715
<i>My childhood a web</i>
<i>of little scams and triumphs.</i>

28
00:02:54,800 --> 00:02:57,917
<i>Parking where you shouldn't.</i>
<i>Drinking after hours.</i>

29
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:00,912
<i>The goods off the back of a lorry.</i>

30
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:04,117
<i>He was lost if he couldn't cheat</i>
<i>in a small way.</i>

31
00:03:04,200 --> 00:03:07,795
<i>My father could talk his way</i>
<i>into and out of anything.</i>

32
00:03:10,280 --> 00:03:13,511
- Tickets, sir.
- Certainly, here you are.

33
00:03:13,600 --> 00:03:15,716
- These are blue tickets, sir.
- Exactly.

34
00:03:15,800 --> 00:03:19,190
That is the whole problem.
I've been sent the wrong tickets.

35
00:03:19,280 --> 00:03:22,431
I'm sorry, sir. This entrance
is for private members only.

36
00:03:22,520 --> 00:03:25,592
- You'll have to go back to queue.
- But I am a member. See?

37
00:03:25,680 --> 00:03:28,717
Simpson, T, Trevor. Doctor, you see?

38
00:03:28,800 --> 00:03:32,236
As a matter of fact, we're in a bit
of a rush. The lad wants a wee-wee.

39
00:03:35,880 --> 00:03:39,839
- All right, Dr Simpson, in you go.
- Thank you very much.

40
00:03:45,120 --> 00:03:48,192
How about that, Blake?
Three bob tickets for just two bob.

41
00:03:48,280 --> 00:03:50,316
Marvellous, bloody marvellous.

42
00:03:51,080 --> 00:03:53,594
<i>My father seemed to me infallible.</i>

43
00:03:53,680 --> 00:03:55,671
<i>Invincible.</i>

44
00:03:55,760 --> 00:03:57,512
<i>Immortal, even.</i>

45
00:04:26,840 --> 00:04:28,796
What do you think?

46
00:04:28,880 --> 00:04:30,996
Very handsome.

47
00:04:32,720 --> 00:04:36,076
- I hope I'm going to get a mention.
- Mention?

48
00:04:36,160 --> 00:04:39,277
- In your acceptance speech.
- Oh, God, a speech.

49
00:04:44,360 --> 00:04:46,920
You really think
I'm going to have to make a speech?

50
00:05:00,280 --> 00:05:03,397
- Do we have time?
- I think so.

51
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:16,718
What's going on in there?

52
00:05:16,800 --> 00:05:19,633
Right on cue.

53
00:05:19,720 --> 00:05:22,393
The sex police.
Be right there, Dad!

54
00:05:22,480 --> 00:05:25,199
We'll be late!
You got two minutes.

55
00:05:26,040 --> 00:05:28,918
Hear that? We got two minutes.

56
00:05:31,080 --> 00:05:35,835
At the risk of getting sentimental, I'd
like to say thank-you to my wife, Kathy.

57
00:05:35,920 --> 00:05:38,388
Not only for all her support
and encouragement,

58
00:05:38,480 --> 00:05:41,392
but because she asked me to mention her.

59
00:05:42,120 --> 00:05:44,350
My dad always used to say,

60
00:05:44,440 --> 00:05:47,238
and I'm sure he'll say it again
before the night's out,

61
00:05:47,320 --> 00:05:50,915
"Being a writer, in particular a poet,
is all well and good.

62
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:53,753
But it's no way to make a living."

63
00:05:53,840 --> 00:05:56,877
Of course, as in most other things,
he's absolutely right.

64
00:05:56,960 --> 00:05:59,520
Too true.

65
00:06:02,440 --> 00:06:05,876
It's nice to be reminded I haven't been
completely wasting my time.

66
00:06:05,960 --> 00:06:08,428
So thank you very much for this.
Thank you.

67
00:06:12,080 --> 00:06:14,196
I wanted him to be a doctor.

68
00:06:14,280 --> 00:06:17,989
Nice pension, surgery, near us.
Take over my surgery for that matter.

69
00:06:18,080 --> 00:06:19,877
Have you actually read the poem?

70
00:06:19,960 --> 00:06:22,110
- 'Course he hasn't read it.
- He's tried.

71
00:06:22,200 --> 00:06:25,033
- Several times.
- Let's have a look then.

72
00:06:25,720 --> 00:06:28,678
- It's plastic.
- I'll take that from you, shall I?

73
00:06:28,760 --> 00:06:30,876
I'm going to the bar.

74
00:06:30,960 --> 00:06:32,518
He could've been a vet even.

75
00:06:39,840 --> 00:06:42,479
Two words, that's all I'd like.
Two words.

76
00:06:42,560 --> 00:06:44,630
- "Well" and "done".
- He doesn't mean it.

77
00:06:44,720 --> 00:06:46,358
He's here for the free buffet.

78
00:06:46,440 --> 00:06:50,274
The mean-spirited, sanctimonious,
narrow-minded old sod.

79
00:06:50,360 --> 00:06:53,796
- What now?
- He's talking to Salman Rushdie.

80
00:06:53,880 --> 00:06:56,314
Look, he's telling him
how it's done.

81
00:06:56,400 --> 00:06:59,995
"Have you read <i>Jaws,</i>
Salman? Now that is a book."

82
00:07:03,720 --> 00:07:06,473
- Together.
- Like this, Granddad?

83
00:07:06,560 --> 00:07:08,949
Oh, now where are you going?

84
00:07:10,680 --> 00:07:11,908
What's that?

85
00:07:12,200 --> 00:07:14,031
Have a guess.

86
00:07:14,120 --> 00:07:17,396
Now bring it to me. No, no, no.

87
00:07:19,600 --> 00:07:23,275
- Ends together. Like that.
- Just leave that, Dad.

88
00:07:23,360 --> 00:07:27,239
I still can't believe you hired a
removal firm. They're rip-off merchants.

89
00:07:27,320 --> 00:07:30,118
We could've done the whole thing
for nothing in the van.

90
00:07:30,200 --> 00:07:34,034
- There was too much stuff for the van.
- You can afford it on what you earn?

91
00:07:35,080 --> 00:07:37,514
Who wants to take mummy
up some breakfast?

92
00:07:37,600 --> 00:07:39,591
- Bye, Granddaddy.
- See you later.

93
00:07:39,680 --> 00:07:41,318
My little helpers!

94
00:07:41,400 --> 00:07:45,188
- I do all right, Dad.
- Why'd you borrow this money off me?

95
00:07:45,280 --> 00:07:48,397
- If you were a doctor...
- A bit late for this conversation.

96
00:07:48,480 --> 00:07:51,153
- What's this doing here?
- It's going in the loft.

97
00:07:51,240 --> 00:07:54,516
- This is Uncle Bert's chandelier.
- It's wire and glass, Dad.

98
00:07:57,080 --> 00:08:00,038
Right. I'm going to need a stepladder.

99
00:08:01,440 --> 00:08:03,431
Phillips screwdriver.

100
00:08:03,520 --> 00:08:05,397
Length of rope.

101
00:08:06,200 --> 00:08:08,236
- Dad?
- It's all right.

102
00:08:08,320 --> 00:08:10,993
Don't fuss. It's nothing.

103
00:08:42,360 --> 00:08:44,954
Your father's going to die, Blake.

104
00:08:45,040 --> 00:08:48,874
Of course we all die sooner or later,
but I'm afraid, with your father,

105
00:08:48,960 --> 00:08:51,110
it will be sooner.

106
00:08:51,200 --> 00:08:53,634
- Will there be pain?
- There shouldn't be.

107
00:08:53,720 --> 00:08:56,871
Not with this kind of cancer.
Usually they just slip away.

108
00:08:59,880 --> 00:09:02,110
- So how long?
- Can't say.

109
00:09:02,200 --> 00:09:04,760
Depends if he feels like fighting.

110
00:09:04,840 --> 00:09:05,989
He knows then?

111
00:09:06,080 --> 00:09:09,550
He asked me the moment he came around.
So I put him in the picture.

112
00:09:14,360 --> 00:09:17,033
- But we do have time?
- That depends.

113
00:09:17,120 --> 00:09:19,475
- Time for what?
- Well, time for...

114
00:09:19,560 --> 00:09:22,074
...you know, putting things in order.

115
00:09:22,760 --> 00:09:26,150
<i>That means you have</i>
<i>to get the conundrum.</i>

116
00:09:26,240 --> 00:09:29,118
<i>If you do, you will win</i>
<i>by just one point.</i>

117
00:09:29,200 --> 00:09:32,715
<i>It's so dramatic, I want to spell it out</i>
<i>so we all know what lies ahead</i>

118
00:09:32,800 --> 00:09:34,916
<i>in the next few seconds. OK.</i>

119
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:37,468
<i>So very intense time for everybody now.</i>

120
00:09:37,560 --> 00:09:41,235
<i>Please now, if everyone's ready,</i>
<i>reveal the final</i>

121
00:09:41,320 --> 00:09:43,629
<i>Countdown Conundrum.</i>

122
00:09:43,720 --> 00:09:46,712
- What did the doctor say?
- He said there's progress.

123
00:09:48,280 --> 00:09:50,350
Said you'd be back home soon.

124
00:09:51,400 --> 00:09:54,198
<i>... young woman was</i>
<i>discovered in a house</i>

125
00:09:54,280 --> 00:09:57,397
<i>in the Clacton area of Leeds</i>
<i>just after midnight last night.</i>

126
00:09:57,480 --> 00:10:00,438
Terrible. Just terrible.

127
00:10:00,520 --> 00:10:03,239
- Know what I'd do?
- Bring back hanging?

128
00:10:05,600 --> 00:10:07,272
Go if you want.

129
00:10:10,520 --> 00:10:12,397
Actually, maybe I will,
if that's OK.

130
00:10:12,480 --> 00:10:15,597
I'll pop back when you're home?
Bring Kathy and the kids?

131
00:10:15,680 --> 00:10:17,671
What do I want visitors for?

132
00:10:17,760 --> 00:10:19,796
Not now, but maybe when you're at home.

133
00:10:19,880 --> 00:10:23,270
Come in, number one. Your time's up.
Number two, your time's up.

134
00:10:23,360 --> 00:10:25,510
Come in, number three.

135
00:10:28,440 --> 00:10:30,635
I'd better go, or I'll miss the train.

136
00:10:30,720 --> 00:10:32,438
See you soon.

137
00:10:35,240 --> 00:10:37,151
We're looking for Arthur Morrison.

138
00:10:37,240 --> 00:10:40,391
Arthur Morrison. Back corridor.

139
00:10:40,480 --> 00:10:41,629
Thank you.

140
00:11:34,880 --> 00:11:37,075
I came as quickly as I could.

141
00:11:37,160 --> 00:11:39,116
Am I too late?

142
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:01,070
Who's that then?

143
00:12:01,160 --> 00:12:02,957
It's Blake, Dad.

144
00:12:03,400 --> 00:12:06,517
Blake. Blake, good.

145
00:12:07,920 --> 00:12:10,070
How did you get from the station?

146
00:12:11,160 --> 00:12:13,151
Taxi.

147
00:12:13,240 --> 00:12:16,596
Taxi, eh? Moneybags.

148
00:12:28,360 --> 00:12:31,158
When did His Lordship arrive?

149
00:12:31,240 --> 00:12:33,231
Just now.

150
00:12:33,880 --> 00:12:35,996
He's with him now.

151
00:12:36,080 --> 00:12:38,992
- Back in London by teatime.
- Gillian.

152
00:12:39,080 --> 00:12:41,833
That's enough.

153
00:12:41,920 --> 00:12:44,718
How's he taking it?

154
00:12:44,800 --> 00:12:47,314
- Don't know yet.
- Hello.

155
00:12:47,400 --> 00:12:49,038
Hi.

156
00:12:49,120 --> 00:12:50,872
All right.

157
00:12:54,600 --> 00:12:56,556
Get off.

158
00:12:57,760 --> 00:13:00,672
- Bloody thing.
- Just trying to remember who you are.

159
00:13:01,880 --> 00:13:04,394
She's just very pleased
to see you.

160
00:13:04,480 --> 00:13:06,948
Arthur's very pleased too.

161
00:13:08,520 --> 00:13:11,637
- Is he?
- Of course he is.

162
00:13:11,720 --> 00:13:16,919
Gosh, "Where's Blake? Where's Blake?"
Is all I've had for days now.

163
00:13:18,040 --> 00:13:21,794
Sorry, I would've gotten down sooner,
it's that new house and everything.

164
00:13:21,880 --> 00:13:24,519
No, it's fine, darling.
He knows how busy you are.

165
00:13:25,280 --> 00:13:27,430
I made up your old bedroom,

166
00:13:27,520 --> 00:13:30,114
when you want to take your stuff up.

167
00:13:30,720 --> 00:13:34,599
Down the corridor, up the stairs,
first on the right.

168
00:13:52,360 --> 00:13:56,911
Blake? Blake, where are you?

169
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:02,309
Come on. She's here.

170
00:14:03,480 --> 00:14:05,948
Come on, chop-chop.

171
00:14:06,040 --> 00:14:09,510
She's here, Blake.
Come and say hello.

172
00:14:14,760 --> 00:14:16,318
Blake!

173
00:14:22,120 --> 00:14:26,636
Sandra, how are you?
I'm Arthur. This is Kim.

174
00:14:26,720 --> 00:14:28,950
This is our youngest, Gillian.

175
00:14:29,040 --> 00:14:31,270
Blake is somewhere,
probably still asleep.

176
00:14:31,360 --> 00:14:34,796
On a beautiful day like today.
Blake, come and say hello to Sandra.

177
00:14:51,680 --> 00:14:54,877
This is the kitchen.
Have you ever cooked on an Aga before?

178
00:14:54,960 --> 00:14:57,235
- No.
- Sandra, would you like a cup of tea?

179
00:14:57,320 --> 00:14:58,309
Yes, please.

180
00:15:01,320 --> 00:15:03,390
There he is! Sleeping Beauty.

181
00:15:03,480 --> 00:15:05,596
Blake, meet Sandra, our new maid.

182
00:15:05,680 --> 00:15:09,195
Maid or housekeeper?
Skivvy! I'm joking.

183
00:15:09,280 --> 00:15:12,431
- Let's just say one of the family.
- Pleased to meet you, Blake.

184
00:15:12,520 --> 00:15:16,115
- You're Scottish.
- Oh, what gave you that impression?

185
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:19,116
- Whereabouts in Scotland?
- Glasgow.

186
00:15:19,200 --> 00:15:23,159
- Oh, Glasgow.
- Ever been to Glasgow?

187
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:25,479
No. No, I haven't.

188
00:15:28,040 --> 00:15:31,510
Right! Well, let me show you your room,
you can get settled in,

189
00:15:31,600 --> 00:15:35,593
and then we'd like you to start
sweeping the chimneys. Just joking.

190
00:15:52,000 --> 00:15:54,070
Follow me, quick as you like.

191
00:15:54,160 --> 00:15:55,593
Mind the step.

192
00:15:55,680 --> 00:15:58,114
On the left,
that's Blake's room.

193
00:15:58,200 --> 00:16:00,191
Avoid at all costs, if I were you.

194
00:16:00,280 --> 00:16:03,716
The last maid we had went in there,
haven't seen her since.

195
00:16:03,800 --> 00:16:06,678
No, seriously, we do have some fun.

196
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:08,672
It was stupid, really.

197
00:16:08,760 --> 00:16:12,389
You spend your life trying to avoid
someone, and then it's too late.

198
00:16:12,480 --> 00:16:14,436
<i>Why can't you talk to him now?</i>

199
00:16:14,520 --> 00:16:16,909
He's so doped up, I could be anyone.

200
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:18,911
<i>I'm sure there'll be time.</i>

201
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:21,833
Yeah, well, you haven't seen him,
have you?

202
00:16:21,920 --> 00:16:24,992
<i>No. No, I suppose not.</i>

203
00:16:27,040 --> 00:16:28,439
The kids are here.

204
00:16:28,520 --> 00:16:30,750
<i>Do you want to talk to them?</i>

205
00:16:30,840 --> 00:16:33,035
No, not just now, eh?

206
00:16:33,120 --> 00:16:35,918
Really? 'Cause they want to talk to you.

207
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:37,991
Yeah, OK, put them on, will you?

208
00:16:39,360 --> 00:16:42,193
- <i>Miss you.</i>
- You too.

209
00:16:50,600 --> 00:16:53,592
He wants you to go through
all the papers.

210
00:16:53,680 --> 00:16:56,399
He thinks I won't understand it.

211
00:16:56,680 --> 00:16:59,069
I'll start tomorrow.

212
00:16:59,800 --> 00:17:01,870
Good luck.

213
00:17:01,960 --> 00:17:05,475
He's got every petrol receipt
since 1949 in there.

214
00:17:07,960 --> 00:17:10,190
And then there's the workshop.

215
00:17:17,560 --> 00:17:20,950
- You seen Sandra much?
- Now and then, yeah.

216
00:17:21,720 --> 00:17:23,517
She's moved into the village.

217
00:17:23,600 --> 00:17:27,229
One of those worker's cottages,
you know?

218
00:17:27,320 --> 00:17:29,117
Divorced.

219
00:17:30,240 --> 00:17:32,276
Why do you ask?

220
00:17:32,360 --> 00:17:34,078
Just curious.

221
00:17:41,680 --> 00:17:45,389
<i>President Kennedy</i>
<i>meanwhile remains incorrigible,</i>

222
00:17:45,480 --> 00:17:49,917
<i>and in a momentous decision, has</i>
<i>ordered an arms blockade of Cuba.</i>

223
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:52,355
<i>This government, as promised...</i>

224
00:17:52,440 --> 00:17:54,237
Missed a bit.

225
00:17:54,320 --> 00:17:57,869
- You could help.
- Sorry. Busy.

226
00:17:57,960 --> 00:18:01,669
- Oh yeah? Doing what?
- Busy smoking my fag.

227
00:18:04,280 --> 00:18:06,032
- Give us a puff.
- No way.

228
00:18:06,120 --> 00:18:07,599
- Go on.
- No.

229
00:18:07,680 --> 00:18:09,636
- What if your dad finds out?
- He won't.

230
00:18:09,720 --> 00:18:12,188
He will. Your dad's all-seeing.

231
00:18:12,280 --> 00:18:14,874
- Like God.
- Omniscient, you mean?

232
00:18:14,960 --> 00:18:17,394
Aye, omni-whatever.

233
00:18:19,880 --> 00:18:22,872
Besides, it's bad for you,
gives you cancer.

234
00:18:22,960 --> 00:18:25,349
So? We'll all be dead soon, anyway.

235
00:18:25,440 --> 00:18:28,750
- Well, you're a little ray of sunshine.
- It's true.

236
00:18:28,840 --> 00:18:32,310
If the Americans invade Cuba,
there'll be nuclear war by Friday.

237
00:18:32,400 --> 00:18:34,914
Just think... dead.

238
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:36,956
And me, still a virgin.

239
00:18:37,960 --> 00:18:40,155
Don't push your luck, Morrison.

240
00:19:43,200 --> 00:19:45,156
You're still here then?

241
00:19:46,680 --> 00:19:48,636
You're not running off?

242
00:19:49,640 --> 00:19:51,756
I'm here for a while, Dad.

243
00:19:52,040 --> 00:19:55,430
Yes, smashing. Smashing.

244
00:20:20,280 --> 00:20:24,876
- I don't understand, what's it for?
- It's for sleeping outdoors.

245
00:20:24,960 --> 00:20:26,996
It's like a normal sleeping bag,

246
00:20:27,080 --> 00:20:31,517
but inside, a waterproof sleeve to keep
out the rain and condensation.

247
00:20:31,600 --> 00:20:33,750
It will render the tent obsolete.

248
00:20:33,840 --> 00:20:37,833
- You'll still get condensation inside.
- No, you won't, 'cause it's plastic.

249
00:20:37,920 --> 00:20:41,196
- It's waterproof, see?
- But condensation's on the inside...

250
00:20:41,280 --> 00:20:45,034
We'll find out when we put it
to the test, won't we, clever-clogs?

251
00:20:49,040 --> 00:20:51,759
- I made two, see?
- What for?

252
00:20:52,680 --> 00:20:54,432
One for me, one for you.

253
00:20:56,880 --> 00:21:00,350
- Thought I'd take the car out.
- Oh, the... the...

254
00:21:00,440 --> 00:21:03,876
The headlights don't work,
so make sure you're back before dark.

255
00:21:03,960 --> 00:21:07,111
He was gonna take it into the garage.

256
00:21:09,120 --> 00:21:10,951
Halfords.

257
00:21:12,320 --> 00:21:13,469
What, love?

258
00:21:13,560 --> 00:21:17,030
New headlights.
Halfords will be cheaper.

259
00:21:23,480 --> 00:21:26,756
Herpes is all right.
It's easily sorted with antibiotics.

260
00:21:26,840 --> 00:21:30,833
But gonorrhoea's a bastard.
Lots of the lads had it in the war.

261
00:21:30,920 --> 00:21:34,799
Once you've seen what a dose of
gonorrhoea can do to a lad's tackle...

262
00:21:34,880 --> 00:21:38,270
I've got pictures in books at home
that'd turn your stomach.

263
00:21:38,360 --> 00:21:40,749
If there's another war
would you get called up?

264
00:21:40,840 --> 00:21:43,991
I wouldn't have thought so.
There's not going be another war.

265
00:21:44,080 --> 00:21:46,958
- You keeping an eye out for the police?
- Yes, Dad.

266
00:21:47,040 --> 00:21:49,315
Self abuse, that's the thing
to be wary of.

267
00:21:49,400 --> 00:21:52,073
- Dad, please...
- It seems like good fun, I know,

268
00:21:52,160 --> 00:21:56,039
but it actually weakens the organ
for married life.

269
00:21:56,120 --> 00:21:58,759
- Police car, right behind us, Dad!
- Really? Where?

270
00:21:58,840 --> 00:22:00,990
Just... over there.

271
00:22:03,640 --> 00:22:06,154
Very funny... very smart.

272
00:22:09,480 --> 00:22:11,710
Bloody marvellous, isn't it?

273
00:22:13,200 --> 00:22:16,033
If they drop the bomb on Leeds,
would it get us up here?

274
00:22:16,120 --> 00:22:18,236
I wouldn't have thought so.

275
00:22:18,320 --> 00:22:20,436
It's God's own country.

276
00:22:20,520 --> 00:22:22,078
What about Mum and Gillian?

277
00:22:22,880 --> 00:22:25,758
I think Mummy and Gillian
will be fine too.

278
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:29,639
What if they drop the bomb on Blackpool?

279
00:22:29,720 --> 00:22:33,474
Why on earth would the communists
want bomb Blackpool, fathead?

280
00:22:34,920 --> 00:22:36,478
Liverpool, then?

281
00:22:36,560 --> 00:22:39,154
It's a bit bloody morbid,
this, isn't it?

282
00:22:39,240 --> 00:22:42,755
Come on, lets go and find somewhere
to camp before it starts raining.

283
00:22:52,960 --> 00:22:57,033
It's a lovely spot. Nice and sheltered,
river nearby for swimming.

284
00:22:58,280 --> 00:23:01,875
- Shouldn't we go to a proper campsite?
- It's the English countryside.

285
00:23:01,960 --> 00:23:03,632
We're English. It belongs to us.

286
00:23:05,080 --> 00:23:08,470
Maybe we should pitch the tent first,
just to be on the safe side.

287
00:23:14,240 --> 00:23:16,515
Is there a canvas bag in there, Blake?

288
00:23:16,600 --> 00:23:19,433
- Yep, yep.
- What's in it?

289
00:23:19,520 --> 00:23:23,035
- Tent pegs.
- No poles?

290
00:23:23,120 --> 00:23:26,192
- No, just some pegs.
- Let's have a look.

291
00:23:29,080 --> 00:23:32,868
Oh, blast! Hell, blast and damnation!

292
00:23:32,960 --> 00:23:34,916
Why didn't you check, fathead?

293
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:37,673
- You packed the tent.
- You used it last, didn't you?

294
00:23:37,760 --> 00:23:41,070
- No, I didn't. You...
- There's no point in arguing about it.

295
00:23:42,760 --> 00:23:45,479
- What you doing?
- Right! Follow me!

296
00:23:51,320 --> 00:23:54,039
- Can't we sleep in the car?
- Sleep in the car?

297
00:23:54,120 --> 00:23:57,715
What's the point of us coming all
the way up here and sleeping in the car?

298
00:23:57,800 --> 00:23:59,995
A hotel then?
Maybe we should just go home.

299
00:24:00,080 --> 00:24:04,153
Look, hold that and stop moaning,
for God's sake.

300
00:24:17,640 --> 00:24:19,631
Mummy says hello.

301
00:24:19,720 --> 00:24:22,109
Pub was bloody miles away.

302
00:24:22,200 --> 00:24:26,079
Felt a bit rude just to use the phone
so stayed for a swift half.

303
00:24:26,160 --> 00:24:28,720
No sandwiches though.
Here you are, supper.

304
00:24:28,800 --> 00:24:31,997
- Not hungry.
- Fair enough. Breakfast then.

305
00:24:36,840 --> 00:24:39,673
Do you want to put the torch out, eh?
Save on batteries.

306
00:24:39,760 --> 00:24:41,751
If you like.

307
00:24:41,840 --> 00:24:44,195
- Night-night, Blake.
- Night.

308
00:25:09,360 --> 00:25:10,679
Dad!

309
00:25:22,240 --> 00:25:24,071
Oh, my book!

310
00:25:24,160 --> 00:25:27,152
It could have been a lot worse.

311
00:25:27,240 --> 00:25:29,231
How, exactly?

312
00:25:29,320 --> 00:25:31,709
If our sleeping bags weren't waterproof.

313
00:25:31,800 --> 00:25:34,360
They're not waterproof!

314
00:25:35,240 --> 00:25:38,471
- They are waterproof.
- So why am I wet, then?

315
00:25:38,560 --> 00:25:41,757
Well, not waterproof, water-resistant.

316
00:25:42,800 --> 00:25:44,358
It's not funny.

317
00:25:45,560 --> 00:25:49,235
- Where are we going?
- I thought I'd drive us up to Scafell.

318
00:25:49,320 --> 00:25:51,595
Can't we just go home?

319
00:25:51,680 --> 00:25:53,910
We've only just started!

320
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:57,037
Besides, the sun will burn this cloud
off in next to no time.

321
00:25:57,120 --> 00:26:01,796
We can dry the tent out on a hedge,
have a picnic and find another spot.

322
00:26:03,120 --> 00:26:04,109
What do you say?

323
00:26:04,200 --> 00:26:07,909
<i>The unrest followed</i>
<i>a radio broadcast in which Khrushchev</i>

324
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:10,309
<i>reiterated his command</i>
<i>missile bases...</i>

325
00:26:10,400 --> 00:26:12,709
I was listening to that!

326
00:26:12,800 --> 00:26:15,997
No point in fretting.
We all have die sooner or later.

327
00:26:16,080 --> 00:26:17,593
If our times up, our times up.

328
00:26:18,680 --> 00:26:20,750
That's more like it. Smashing.

329
00:26:56,360 --> 00:26:59,352
I'm not going swimming,
if that's what you're thinking.

330
00:27:00,120 --> 00:27:02,759
- I'm wet enough, as it is.
- Right, budge over, you!

331
00:27:02,840 --> 00:27:06,310
- What for?
- Time you learnt to drive.

332
00:27:06,600 --> 00:27:08,397
You're joking?

333
00:27:08,480 --> 00:27:09,595
What, here?

334
00:27:09,680 --> 00:27:11,875
Here there's no one
for you to smash into.

335
00:27:11,960 --> 00:27:14,076
Come on, budge over!

336
00:27:17,880 --> 00:27:22,271
Very gently off the clutch.
No, gently! Gently! Stop!

337
00:27:23,360 --> 00:27:27,069
First gear. Top left.
Top left, that's it. Come on.

338
00:27:27,160 --> 00:27:29,549
Come on. Gently!

339
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:33,151
- Clutch! No, fathead, left foot.
- You told me...

340
00:27:33,240 --> 00:27:36,516
That's it. Now gently.
Second into third.

341
00:27:36,600 --> 00:27:38,318
That's it, that's it. Good.

342
00:27:38,400 --> 00:27:40,675
Now gently away. Good.

343
00:27:40,760 --> 00:27:44,435
Excellent. Now indicate.
Indicate right. Come on, indicate right!

344
00:27:44,520 --> 00:27:45,999
- OK!
- Now, indicate left!

345
00:27:46,080 --> 00:27:48,753
- Indicate left.
- What am I indicating for?

346
00:27:48,840 --> 00:27:52,515
- Because you mustn't get in bad habits.
- There's no one here, Dad.

347
00:27:52,600 --> 00:27:55,797
Come on! Hard round,
left hand down. That's it.

348
00:27:55,880 --> 00:27:59,873
- Now, right hand down.
- Dad! Please!

349
00:28:04,440 --> 00:28:07,955
Faster, don't worry about it.
Don't be scared, just go faster.

350
00:28:08,040 --> 00:28:09,917
- It's a bit fast.
- You can go faster.

351
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:11,672
Faster than this?

352
00:28:16,040 --> 00:28:18,634
Quick! Come on! That's it!

353
00:28:18,720 --> 00:28:21,359
Excellent, do you like it?
Good. Are you ready?

354
00:28:21,440 --> 00:28:23,431
One... two... three!

355
00:28:23,520 --> 00:28:24,999
Now!

356
00:28:40,240 --> 00:28:43,073
Come on. Come on.

357
00:28:44,280 --> 00:28:46,077
Come on out, you little sod!

358
00:28:50,000 --> 00:28:52,594
Come on. Come on, get up.

359
00:29:27,760 --> 00:29:29,113
- Hello?
- <i>Hi.</i>

360
00:29:29,200 --> 00:29:31,919
- Oh, it's you.
- <i>Who else were you expecting?</i>

361
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:34,355
I just... I thought it might be mum.

362
00:29:34,440 --> 00:29:37,159
I'm walking the dog.
Mind if I call you when I get back?

363
00:29:37,240 --> 00:29:39,071
<i>Yeah, yeah, sure.</i>

364
00:29:41,120 --> 00:29:43,680
- As soon as I get in. Bye.
- <i>Bye.</i>

365
00:29:43,760 --> 00:29:46,911
Come on... Stupid, stupid, stupid.

366
00:29:51,280 --> 00:29:54,909
- <i>Sending you mad is he?</i>
- <i>I'm getting your migraines.</i>

367
00:29:55,800 --> 00:29:57,472
Can't you come and rescue me?

368
00:29:57,560 --> 00:30:01,678
<i>Sorry, love, it's men only.</i>
<i>You're on your own, I'm afraid.</i>

369
00:30:01,760 --> 00:30:04,149
Did he blame me for that
tent pole business?

370
00:30:04,240 --> 00:30:06,276
<i>What tent pole business?</i>

371
00:30:06,360 --> 00:30:10,512
- Didn't he tell you last night?
- <i>I took a sleeping pill. Why?</i>

372
00:30:10,600 --> 00:30:13,114
<i>What happened with the tent poles?</i>

373
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:16,673
<i>Blake? You there?</i>

374
00:30:17,680 --> 00:30:19,796
He woke me at six in the morning!

375
00:30:19,880 --> 00:30:22,553
That's never happened before.
Something must be up.

376
00:30:22,640 --> 00:30:27,555
I wasn't far wrong. I realised we were
sleeping in two foot of water.

377
00:30:27,640 --> 00:30:29,835
The bloody stream had burst it's banks.

378
00:30:29,920 --> 00:30:33,549
Blake gave me a look like thunder.
I thought he was going to punch me one.

379
00:30:33,640 --> 00:30:35,551
Excuse me a minute.

380
00:30:38,040 --> 00:30:41,953
Here you are, a present for you.
Don't tell Mummy. You'll get me shot.

381
00:30:42,600 --> 00:30:44,431
- Where are you going?
- Phone her.

382
00:30:44,520 --> 00:30:46,476
What, again?

383
00:30:46,560 --> 00:30:49,154
I just want to make sure
she's managing without us.

384
00:30:49,240 --> 00:30:52,789
If anyone asks, you're 36!

385
00:31:07,120 --> 00:31:09,634
I wish you were here too.

386
00:31:10,240 --> 00:31:13,232
I know, but what can we do?

387
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:17,833
Don't be daft. You know I do.

388
00:31:19,560 --> 00:31:23,599
Well, there's no point in worrying
about it. Everything's gonna be fine.

389
00:31:23,680 --> 00:31:26,194
After all, where's the harm?

390
00:31:27,080 --> 00:31:30,311
Yes. Yeah, we will, we will.

391
00:31:58,160 --> 00:32:00,913
How are you doing, Stirling Moss?
Behaving yourself?

392
00:32:02,160 --> 00:32:05,357
- Right, one for the road?
- I'm going to bed.

393
00:32:05,440 --> 00:32:07,032
Good idea.

394
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:10,070
- How was Mum?
- What?

395
00:32:10,160 --> 00:32:12,879
Oh, she was asleep.
I said I'd call her in the morning.

396
00:32:12,960 --> 00:32:16,555
- Hey, Arthur? Have you heard the news?
- No, turn it up.

397
00:32:16,640 --> 00:32:19,438
<i>Soviet missiles</i>
<i>should be removed from Cuba</i>

398
00:32:19,520 --> 00:32:21,988
<i>under United Nations supervision.</i>

399
00:32:22,080 --> 00:32:24,913
<i>Further details of the deal</i>
<i>have yet to become clear.</i>

400
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:29,630
<i>But it seems that for tonight, at least,</i>
<i>the world can sleep a little safer.</i>

401
00:32:33,240 --> 00:32:36,949
What did I tell you? No point in getting
worked up about it, was there?

402
00:32:37,040 --> 00:32:38,871
Are you all right?

403
00:32:42,080 --> 00:32:44,878
So... to Kennedy, then.

404
00:32:44,960 --> 00:32:46,996
To Kennedy.

405
00:32:50,240 --> 00:32:54,153
That went down well.
Think I can sneak in one more.

406
00:33:13,080 --> 00:33:15,958
I think I'll pop you
in the boot too.

407
00:33:16,040 --> 00:33:20,556
- Why can't you go instead?
- Not today, Blake.

408
00:33:20,640 --> 00:33:23,598
Why? Have you got one
of your migraines?

409
00:33:26,520 --> 00:33:30,718
No. Not yet, anyway.

410
00:33:30,800 --> 00:33:33,997
No, I've got patients to see,
that's all.

411
00:33:34,080 --> 00:33:38,198
Somebody's got to keep that surgery
running while Dad is off gadding about.

412
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:43,072
But why does Aunty Beaty
always have to come?

413
00:33:44,160 --> 00:33:47,277
Well, because your Aunty Beaty
gets a bit blue.

414
00:33:47,360 --> 00:33:52,036
- And your Dad likes cheering her up.
- I'd still prefer it if you came.

415
00:33:52,120 --> 00:33:55,874
Would you stop grizzling,
for goodness sake!

416
00:33:57,720 --> 00:34:00,234
Look, darling, I'm sorry.

417
00:34:02,600 --> 00:34:04,795
But you'll have fun. Go on.

418
00:34:04,880 --> 00:34:07,678
Go on. OK.

419
00:34:10,160 --> 00:34:12,390
Oh, one more!

420
00:34:13,720 --> 00:34:15,950
One, two, three!

421
00:34:51,440 --> 00:34:54,352
Let's get you down.
Come on, let's have some lunch.

422
00:34:54,440 --> 00:34:58,149
Boom-boom. Boom-boom.
Boom-boom. Boom-boom.

423
00:34:58,240 --> 00:35:00,674
Can you hear it?

424
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:03,355
Pumping away?

425
00:35:04,960 --> 00:35:06,678
Can I have a go?

426
00:35:08,960 --> 00:35:11,633
Blake, you and Gillian
take Josie down the hill

427
00:35:11,720 --> 00:35:14,154
whilst Aunty Beaty and I
get the picnic ready.

428
00:35:15,280 --> 00:35:18,716
- Arthur, I don't think...
- No, no. Nonsense.

429
00:35:18,800 --> 00:35:20,950
You can look after the ladies,
can't you?

430
00:35:21,040 --> 00:35:23,235
Big, strong lad like you.

431
00:35:23,320 --> 00:35:24,992
Go on, off you go!

432
00:35:46,440 --> 00:35:48,396
What are you doing, Blake?

433
00:35:48,480 --> 00:35:51,313
- What does it look like?
- Stop showing off. You'll fall!

434
00:35:51,400 --> 00:35:55,678
- I won't fall.
- Blake, come down. You're too high!

435
00:35:56,160 --> 00:35:57,957
Blake!

436
00:36:09,080 --> 00:36:10,911
- Blake!
- Blake!

437
00:36:11,720 --> 00:36:14,757
Blake!

438
00:36:39,880 --> 00:36:44,237
Blake, what the hell do you think you're
playing at, sneaking up on people?

439
00:36:44,320 --> 00:36:46,834
I fell out of a tree.

440
00:36:46,920 --> 00:36:49,354
How did you get up a tree? Fly up?

441
00:36:50,920 --> 00:36:53,229
I don't think
we're going to have to amputate.

442
00:36:53,320 --> 00:36:56,039
But I am going to put
some antiseptic on it.

443
00:36:56,120 --> 00:36:59,635
And that's going to sting a bit.
Brave enough?

444
00:37:02,600 --> 00:37:06,991
Now, that's it. You take
that end, now take this end...

445
00:37:07,680 --> 00:37:09,272
Now...

446
00:37:09,360 --> 00:37:11,828
...best not to tell Mummy
about any of this, eh?

447
00:37:11,920 --> 00:37:14,150
You'll get me in trouble.
Is that a deal?

448
00:37:16,200 --> 00:37:19,112
Now remember, big boys don't cry.

449
00:37:19,200 --> 00:37:21,430
Especially not in front of girls.

450
00:37:22,080 --> 00:37:24,435
Show them how brave you are!

451
00:37:24,520 --> 00:37:26,238
All right?

452
00:37:27,800 --> 00:37:29,358
Good boy.

453
00:37:33,160 --> 00:37:35,549
Another swig of wine, please.

454
00:37:51,920 --> 00:37:55,515
"Swig." Funny word, "swig."

455
00:37:57,960 --> 00:38:00,474
Have you been through the papers yet?

456
00:38:00,560 --> 00:38:02,949
The stocks and tax and stuff?

457
00:38:03,560 --> 00:38:05,152
Not yet, Dad. No.

458
00:38:05,240 --> 00:38:07,959
Have a look at it all, will you?

459
00:38:08,040 --> 00:38:10,270
Your Mother's a bit scared of it,
I think.

460
00:38:10,360 --> 00:38:11,679
I will, yes.

461
00:38:13,080 --> 00:38:15,196
Sometime soon, all right?

462
00:38:33,400 --> 00:38:34,992
Who's that?

463
00:38:36,200 --> 00:38:37,952
Robert Morrison.

464
00:38:38,040 --> 00:38:42,113
Died 1948, run over by a horse.

465
00:38:45,480 --> 00:38:46,674
Drunk, probably.

466
00:38:56,640 --> 00:38:58,756
It says here that Daniel Morrison...

467
00:38:58,840 --> 00:39:01,593
...married his wife's sister
as well as his wife.

468
00:39:01,680 --> 00:39:06,231
Yes, his first wife died in
childbirth, and he married the sister.

469
00:39:06,320 --> 00:39:09,756
Yes, God, you weren't allowed
to mention Daniel, either.

470
00:39:09,840 --> 00:39:13,594
- All this scandal.
- Well...

471
00:39:13,680 --> 00:39:15,398
...now it can come out.

472
00:39:16,520 --> 00:39:18,158
What did Granddad die of, Mum?

473
00:39:19,600 --> 00:39:22,876
Oh... cancer, I think. Yeah.

474
00:39:22,960 --> 00:39:25,155
- Bowel?
- Mm-hmm.

475
00:39:27,560 --> 00:39:30,711
I think you've one
or two more years yet, Blake.

