723
00:58:21,120 --> 00:58:25,636
Blake! Blake!
Come back! Don't be like that.

724
00:58:25,720 --> 00:58:28,598
Come and have a drink.
It was just a bit of fun.

725
00:58:28,680 --> 00:58:31,638
Yeah, for you and your girlfriend,
maybe.

726
00:58:31,720 --> 00:58:34,188
Honestly, an old man like you?

727
00:58:34,280 --> 00:58:37,636
It's pathetic. You'd think Beaty
would be enough for you.

728
00:58:37,720 --> 00:58:38,789
I beg your pardon?

729
00:58:38,880 --> 00:58:41,553
I'm surprised you didn't
ask her along on holiday.

730
00:58:41,640 --> 00:58:44,234
- She goes every where else with us.
- Enough, Blake.

731
00:58:44,320 --> 00:58:46,880
- I'm sure Mummy wouldn't mind.
- Blake.

732
00:58:46,960 --> 00:58:49,349
And even if she does mind,
what do you care?

733
00:58:49,440 --> 00:58:52,193
- "It's just a bit of fun."
- I said that's enough!

734
00:58:53,400 --> 00:58:55,550
I love your mother very much.

735
00:58:56,280 --> 00:58:58,236
I love all of you.

736
00:58:59,080 --> 00:59:01,958
You mean the whole world to me.
You know that.

737
00:59:02,040 --> 00:59:05,157
So why'd you do it, Dad? Why?

738
00:59:05,240 --> 00:59:07,276
I don't know what
you're talking about.

739
00:59:07,360 --> 00:59:09,635
Now come inside.

740
00:59:46,000 --> 00:59:47,672
Hello, stranger.

741
00:59:47,760 --> 00:59:50,274
So, what was it like then?

742
00:59:50,360 --> 00:59:53,909
- All right for some.
- Meet nice girls when you were away?

743
00:59:54,000 --> 00:59:56,150
Any holiday romance?

744
00:59:56,240 --> 00:59:59,550
- Only for Dad.
- I just hope you weren't unfaithful.

745
00:59:59,640 --> 01:00:02,791
If I found out you been seeing someone
else behind my back...

746
01:00:02,880 --> 01:00:04,598
Blake, get off.

747
01:00:44,080 --> 01:00:45,399
Blake?

748
01:00:45,480 --> 01:00:47,994
Blake?

749
01:00:48,080 --> 01:00:49,877
Won't be a minute.

750
01:00:53,520 --> 01:00:56,796
He was trying to get up
to clear his lungs and...

751
01:00:56,880 --> 01:00:58,996
And he was coughing a lot

752
01:00:59,080 --> 01:01:01,799
and panicking,
so I gave him some morphine.

753
01:01:03,360 --> 01:01:07,194
He... all he said was,
"Can I lie down now?"

754
01:01:08,080 --> 01:01:10,389
He's better now, but...

755
01:01:10,480 --> 01:01:12,550
...his breathing's very irregular.

756
01:01:15,800 --> 01:01:17,711
What's he looking at?

757
01:01:17,800 --> 01:01:20,473
Nothing.

758
01:01:22,320 --> 01:01:24,038
Dad?

759
01:01:27,400 --> 01:01:29,470
He's looking straight through me.

760
01:01:39,240 --> 01:01:43,392
<i>Please, Dad, stop breathing.</i>
<i>Please just stop.</i>

761
01:01:44,280 --> 01:01:47,113
<i>If you can't come back</i>
<i>as you were, then go.</i>

762
01:02:04,160 --> 01:02:05,957
Thank God.

763
01:02:06,040 --> 01:02:07,678
I thought he'd gone then.

764
01:02:08,960 --> 01:02:12,999
Don't do that again. Silly old bugger.

765
01:02:16,320 --> 01:02:19,039
- <i>I hate him.</i>
- <i>Don't be daft.</i>

766
01:02:19,120 --> 01:02:22,635
- No one hates their dad, not really.
- Well, I do.

767
01:02:23,440 --> 01:02:25,237
All I mean is...

768
01:02:25,320 --> 01:02:29,154
...if there's a firing squad and
I had to choose between shooting you

769
01:02:29,240 --> 01:02:30,912
or shooting my dad,

770
01:02:31,000 --> 01:02:33,116
then I'd shoot my dad, that's all.

771
01:02:36,040 --> 01:02:38,190
- What was that for? What?
- You know what.

772
01:02:38,280 --> 01:02:40,874
- Don't you dare.
- I was trying to be nice...

773
01:02:40,960 --> 01:02:43,315
Well it's not nice.
It's a wicked thing to say.

774
01:02:43,400 --> 01:02:46,233
Don't you dare ever, ever say anything
like that again.

775
01:02:46,320 --> 01:02:47,958
- Why not?
- It doesn't matter.

776
01:02:48,040 --> 01:02:51,237
I wouldn't say that about my dad,
and he's a vicious bastard.

777
01:02:51,320 --> 01:02:54,471
- All I meant...
- You should never wish anyone dead.

778
01:02:54,560 --> 01:02:56,391
What if it came true?

779
01:02:59,280 --> 01:03:02,477
- Blake? Blake, where are you?
- Sex police! Go!

780
01:03:05,840 --> 01:03:07,990
- Arthur!
- Sandra! Sorry.

781
01:03:08,080 --> 01:03:09,638
Why don't you knock?

782
01:03:09,720 --> 01:03:11,438
You frightened the life out of me!

783
01:03:11,520 --> 01:03:14,080
I didn't think you'd be in, sorry.

784
01:03:14,160 --> 01:03:17,789
I was just looking
for Blake, that's all.

785
01:03:17,880 --> 01:03:20,075
Oh, well, he's hardly likely to be here.

786
01:03:20,160 --> 01:03:23,311
No, I suppose not.
But tell him...

787
01:03:23,400 --> 01:03:27,598
Tell Blake I was looking for him. Sorry.

788
01:03:46,480 --> 01:03:48,755
It's ten minutes now.

789
01:03:49,560 --> 01:03:51,596
I think he's gone, Blake.

790
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:12,513
Should I cover his face?

791
01:04:12,600 --> 01:04:14,318
No.

792
01:04:21,640 --> 01:04:22,959
You'll be all right here?

793
01:04:23,040 --> 01:04:26,350
Yeah, I thought I might just lie down
with him for a bit.

794
01:04:26,440 --> 01:04:28,271
Do you think?

795
01:04:28,360 --> 01:04:31,477
- Do you think that's all right?
- I'm sure it is.

796
01:05:34,680 --> 01:05:36,159
Mom.

797
01:05:38,680 --> 01:05:40,511
Mom?

798
01:05:43,000 --> 01:05:44,831
The undertaker's here.

799
01:05:46,680 --> 01:05:48,989
What?

800
01:05:49,080 --> 01:05:51,514
The undertaker's here.

801
01:06:27,880 --> 01:06:28,915
He's still warm.

802
01:06:29,000 --> 01:06:31,434
That's why we like
to get in pretty sharpish,

803
01:06:31,520 --> 01:06:35,274
before the rigor mortis. After 12 hours,
they get stiff as a board.

804
01:06:37,200 --> 01:06:39,031
Hello, what's this?

805
01:06:39,120 --> 01:06:40,269
Pacemaker.

806
01:06:40,360 --> 01:06:42,954
- Cremation is it?
- I think so, yes.

807
01:06:43,040 --> 01:06:45,918
Well, I'll have to remove that
I'm afraid.

808
01:06:46,000 --> 01:06:48,719
Otherwise they explode.

809
01:06:48,800 --> 01:06:51,155
I'll... I'll make a note of it.

810
01:07:14,240 --> 01:07:18,153
<i>Boom-boom. Boom-boom.</i>
<i>Boom-boom. Boom-boom.</i>

811
01:07:19,480 --> 01:07:21,471
<i>Can you hear it?</i>

812
01:07:22,920 --> 01:07:24,876
<i>Pumping away?</i>

813
01:07:53,600 --> 01:07:56,068
I was just passing, so I thought...

814
01:07:56,160 --> 01:07:58,754
Not exactly
on your way home, though, is it?

815
01:07:58,840 --> 01:08:00,910
Nope.

816
01:08:01,000 --> 01:08:02,718
Poor old King Arthur.

817
01:08:04,120 --> 01:08:06,429
Lent me the money for this house,
you know?

818
01:08:07,400 --> 01:08:09,994
I won't half miss him.

819
01:08:10,080 --> 01:08:12,310
You know, I used to think
you fancied him.

820
01:08:12,920 --> 01:08:14,319
But I was shagging you.

821
01:08:14,400 --> 01:08:16,516
I thought you were
with him on the sly.

822
01:08:16,600 --> 01:08:20,229
Christ, Blake. What did you take me for?

823
01:08:21,280 --> 01:08:23,794
Remember how he was always
trying to catch us?

824
01:08:23,880 --> 01:08:26,678
Sex police? Never did though, did he?

825
01:08:27,440 --> 01:08:28,839
Too fast for him.

826
01:08:30,320 --> 01:08:31,355
He used to say,

827
01:08:31,440 --> 01:08:34,716
"Leave two blokes in a room
long enough, they'll kill each other.

828
01:08:34,800 --> 01:08:37,598
Leave a man and a woman,
and they'll screw each other."

829
01:08:37,680 --> 01:08:39,079
Is that right?

830
01:08:41,600 --> 01:08:44,114
You were my first love,
you know that, don't you?

831
01:08:45,640 --> 01:08:47,039
Yeah, well...

832
01:08:47,880 --> 01:08:49,996
...life's easier without.

833
01:08:52,480 --> 01:08:54,152
It's funny, though, isn't it?

834
01:08:55,040 --> 01:08:57,713
You and me. Alone together again.

835
01:08:57,800 --> 01:08:59,711
I mean, he's not here to walk in on us.

836
01:08:59,800 --> 01:09:01,677
Blake.

837
01:09:12,520 --> 01:09:15,318
It's all right. Look at you.

838
01:09:16,800 --> 01:09:18,995
Sorry. I'm sorry.

839
01:09:36,640 --> 01:09:38,517
Hey, you want to see something?

840
01:09:43,440 --> 01:09:46,159
- It's his pacemaker.
- Bloody hell, Blake!

841
01:09:46,240 --> 01:09:49,596
The undertaker cut it out of his chest
with a scalpel.

842
01:09:51,600 --> 01:09:53,875
I washed it.

843
01:09:53,960 --> 01:09:56,269
Did you see him cut it out?

844
01:09:56,360 --> 01:09:57,634
Nope.

845
01:09:58,880 --> 01:10:00,677
I wanted to, though.

846
01:10:00,760 --> 01:10:04,230
I wanted to see if I could take it,
watching him being cut open.

847
01:10:04,640 --> 01:10:07,359
See if I could have been
a doctor too, I suppose.

848
01:10:08,320 --> 01:10:10,595
- You think I've gone nuts, don't you?
- Yeah.

849
01:10:12,120 --> 01:10:14,190
But then you always were
a wee bit nuts.

850
01:10:16,720 --> 01:10:18,756
I'm back.

851
01:10:25,440 --> 01:10:27,908
- Hello.
- Hello.

852
01:10:29,560 --> 01:10:31,391
Oh, God, it's good to see you.

853
01:10:32,000 --> 01:10:33,831
I'm so sorry.

854
01:11:24,360 --> 01:11:26,476
I'm sorry.

855
01:11:26,560 --> 01:11:28,835
This isn't working, is it?

856
01:11:30,360 --> 01:11:32,316
It's OK.

857
01:11:33,880 --> 01:11:36,155
You just lie still.

858
01:11:51,320 --> 01:11:53,515
How are you feeling?

859
01:11:54,360 --> 01:11:56,396
I don't know.

860
01:12:01,600 --> 01:12:03,192
Cheated.

861
01:12:30,160 --> 01:12:33,709
- Do you want to go into the car?
- Yes, come on.

862
01:12:38,840 --> 01:12:41,832
- Oh, where'd you get that from?
- Dad's wardrobe.

863
01:12:41,920 --> 01:12:45,674
- A bit loose around the belly.
- No, no, it's not that loose.

864
01:12:46,440 --> 01:12:48,795
- You don't mind, do you?
- Not at all.

865
01:12:48,880 --> 01:12:51,633
No, I'm sure he'd be delighted.

866
01:13:44,640 --> 01:13:46,392
What's up?

867
01:14:30,440 --> 01:14:33,079
Come on, you're meant to be bartending.

868
01:14:33,160 --> 01:14:35,594
- I still can't see it.
- See what?

869
01:14:35,680 --> 01:14:37,557
The resemblance.

870
01:14:37,640 --> 01:14:40,791
Oh, for Christ's sake, Blake,
why can't you just let it go?

871
01:14:40,880 --> 01:14:43,189
It's history.

872
01:14:50,120 --> 01:14:52,031
Would you like a drink,
Aunty Beaty?

873
01:14:52,120 --> 01:14:55,510
Oh, I don't think anyone's called me
"Aunty" in 20 years.

874
01:14:55,600 --> 01:14:57,352
Look at you, Blake.

875
01:14:57,440 --> 01:15:01,149
Goodness. Well, you look just like him.

876
01:15:01,240 --> 01:15:04,152
I think Gill needs a hand, Mum.

877
01:15:04,240 --> 01:15:06,356
Does she?

878
01:15:06,440 --> 01:15:10,228
- All right, dear.
- You sound just like him too.

879
01:15:10,320 --> 01:15:13,073
- Beaty, can I have a word?
- Yes, of course.

880
01:15:13,160 --> 01:15:15,355
In private.

881
01:15:16,360 --> 01:15:20,831
The thing is, I do know something
went on between you and Dad.

882
01:15:20,920 --> 01:15:22,990
- I see.
- I know it was a long time ago.

883
01:15:23,080 --> 01:15:25,833
I'm not angry.
I mean, I was angry.

884
01:15:26,720 --> 01:15:30,429
For years, furious
with him mainly, but...

885
01:15:30,520 --> 01:15:32,112
But I'm not anymore.

886
01:15:32,200 --> 01:15:34,156
At least I don't think so.

887
01:15:34,640 --> 01:15:37,473
But I would like to know the truth.

888
01:15:37,560 --> 01:15:40,279
I need to know the truth.
I think I'll go mad otherwise.

889
01:15:40,360 --> 01:15:42,669
You can't understand that, can you?

890
01:15:42,760 --> 01:15:45,752
Well, yes. Yes, I suppose so.

891
01:15:49,120 --> 01:15:53,796
Well, mine was never a very happy
marriage, Blake. And Arthur...

892
01:15:53,880 --> 01:15:57,634
...patron saint of lost causes,
he saw that and he...

893
01:15:57,720 --> 01:15:59,870
...consoled me, I suppose.

894
01:16:00,720 --> 01:16:03,154
I was lonely, and he made me laugh.

895
01:16:04,280 --> 01:16:06,840
I wouldn't have got
through the days without him.

896
01:16:07,840 --> 01:16:10,400
It was consolation, Blake.

897
01:16:10,480 --> 01:16:13,233
- But was it physical?
- Is that important?

898
01:16:13,320 --> 01:16:15,151
Yes, I think it is.

899
01:16:16,280 --> 01:16:19,750
Leave me something
of him please, Blake. It is mine.

900
01:16:34,160 --> 01:16:36,230
Whatever sadness,

901
01:16:37,200 --> 01:16:40,476
whatever hurt we caused you,
I am sorry for.

902
01:16:42,400 --> 01:16:44,595
All I will say is this:

903
01:16:46,840 --> 01:16:51,436
Arthur loved your mother more than
any human being on the whole earth.

904
01:16:51,520 --> 01:16:53,636
And you too. You and Gill.

905
01:16:55,320 --> 01:16:57,709
And he was proud of you.

906
01:16:58,560 --> 01:17:01,233
So, so proud.

907
01:17:01,320 --> 01:17:04,073
Even if he didn't always show it.

908
01:17:10,200 --> 01:17:12,031
But what about Josie?

909
01:17:14,080 --> 01:17:15,638
Do I have a sister?

910
01:17:18,320 --> 01:17:21,630
Oh, there you are.
The taxi's been waiting, Mum.

911
01:17:21,720 --> 01:17:24,029
- Sorry.
- We've got to go.

912
01:17:28,320 --> 01:17:30,993
I'm gonna miss him so much.

913
01:17:56,560 --> 01:17:58,232
Goodbye.

914
01:18:13,960 --> 01:18:15,678
<i>Blake!</i>

915
01:18:29,640 --> 01:18:32,552
- Sure you don't want me to drive you?
- No, Dad.

916
01:18:32,640 --> 01:18:34,835
I can run you to the station
in ten minutes.

917
01:18:34,920 --> 01:18:37,115
I prefer this way really.

918
01:18:37,880 --> 01:18:40,030
How far are your digs at the other end?

919
01:18:40,120 --> 01:18:41,951
Couple of miles.

920
01:18:42,600 --> 01:18:45,398
- How you going to get there?
- I don't know.

921
01:18:45,480 --> 01:18:48,677
- Bus, I suppose.
- Bus? With all this stuff?

922
01:18:48,760 --> 01:18:51,115
- Or taxi.
- Oh, a taxi!

923
01:18:51,200 --> 01:18:53,350
- Is that right, moneybags?
- Dad.

924
01:18:53,440 --> 01:18:56,910
Once your allowance is gone, that's it.
Don't come running cap in hand.

925
01:18:57,000 --> 01:18:59,798
- Doesn't grow on trees.
- Doesn't grow on trees. I know.

926
01:19:00,240 --> 01:19:02,310
You're studying a proper subject,

927
01:19:02,400 --> 01:19:04,868
like medicine or science,
guarantee you a job.

928
01:19:04,960 --> 01:19:07,076
Dad, please.

929
01:19:07,800 --> 01:19:10,075
Right then.

930
01:19:11,560 --> 01:19:13,391
See you then.

931
01:19:13,480 --> 01:19:15,277
See you, Dad.

932
01:19:20,640 --> 01:19:22,358
TTFM.

933
01:19:24,200 --> 01:19:26,191
I'll miss you.

934
01:19:33,000 --> 01:19:35,309
You too, Dad.

935
01:20:26,160 --> 01:20:27,912
Dad.

936
01:20:50,320 --> 01:20:53,596
<i>When did you last</i>
<i>see your father?</i>

937
01:20:53,680 --> 01:20:56,433
<i>Was it when they burnt the coffin?</i>

938
01:20:56,520 --> 01:20:58,192
<i>Put the lid on it?</i>

939
01:21:00,400 --> 01:21:02,391
<i>When he exhaled his last breath?</i>

940
01:21:03,360 --> 01:21:05,191
<i>When he sat up</i>
<i>and said something?</i>

941
01:21:09,360 --> 01:21:11,078
<i>When he last recognized you?</i>

942
01:21:11,960 --> 01:21:13,552
<i>When he last smiled?</i>

943
01:21:24,440 --> 01:21:26,590
<i>When did you last see your father?</i>

944
01:21:27,440 --> 01:21:29,670
<i>The last time he was healthy, active?</i>

945
01:21:30,800 --> 01:21:33,951
<i>The last time you had</i>
<i>an argument about something?</i>

946
01:21:37,040 --> 01:21:38,712
Dear old Dad.

947
01:21:41,640 --> 01:21:43,915
Want to keep this,
in case it comes in useful?

948
01:21:44,000 --> 01:21:44,989
No.

949
01:21:45,080 --> 01:21:46,991
- Yes, I can.
- No, you can't.

950
01:21:47,840 --> 01:21:51,310
Dad would have done, you know?

951
01:21:51,400 --> 01:21:53,595
<i>Those weeks</i>
<i>we tried to say goodbye</i>

952
01:21:53,680 --> 01:21:55,557
<i>were like a series of depletions.</i>

953
01:21:55,640 --> 01:21:58,950
<i>Each day I thought, "He can't get</i>
<i>less like himself than this. "

954
01:21:59,480 --> 01:22:01,471
<i>Yet each day he did.</i>

955
01:22:02,480 --> 01:22:06,029
<i>So I've been trying to recall</i>
<i>the last time I actually saw him.</i>

956
01:22:06,120 --> 01:22:09,112
<i>The last time he was unmistakably there,</i>

957
01:22:09,960 --> 01:22:11,837
<i>in the fullness of being...</i>

958
01:22:12,680 --> 01:22:15,399
<i>... him.</i>

959
01:22:24,560 --> 01:22:27,552
- What are you doing?
- I'm doing it as fast as I can.

960
01:22:27,640 --> 01:22:29,790
- You using a Phillips screwdriver?
- No.

961
01:22:29,880 --> 01:22:31,836
- No wonder you can't do it.
- I can do it.

962
01:22:31,920 --> 01:22:33,638
- Doesn't look like it.
- Dad.

963
01:22:33,720 --> 01:22:36,154
- Are you sure it's gonna hold?
- Absolutely.

964
01:22:36,240 --> 01:22:38,470
Right, let's see.
Ready to let go?

965
01:22:38,560 --> 01:22:40,073
Absolutely.

966
01:22:40,160 --> 01:22:41,559
Gently does it.

967
01:22:43,040 --> 01:22:45,235
- There.
- Told you, didn't I?

968
01:22:51,640 --> 01:22:53,471
